b'' b"following is a short note commenting on den boer and bosselaers'" b'recent work on the md5 message-digest algorithm. feel free to email' b'questions or further comments.' b'' b'-- burt kaliski' b'rsa laboratories' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'\\documentstyle[12pt]{article}' b'\\begin{document}' b'' b"\\title{on ``pseudocollisions'' in the md5 message-digest algorithm}" b'\\author{burton s. kaliski jr. b'matthew j.b. robshaw b'rsa laboratories b'100 marine parkway b'redwood city, ca b'\\date{april b'' b'\\maketitle' b'' b'a message-digest algorithm maps a message of arbitrary length to a' b"``digest'' of fixed length, and has three properties: computing the" b'digest is easy, finding a message with a given' b"digest---``inversion''---is hard, and finding two messages with the" b"same digest---``collision''---is also hard. message-digest algorithms" b'have many applications, including digital signatures and message' b'authentication.' b'' b"rsa data security's md5 message-digest algorithm, developed by ron" b'rivest \\cite{rfc-md5}, maps a message to a 128-bit message digest.' b'computing the digest of a one-megabyte message takes as little as a' b'second. while no message-digest algorithm can yet be {\\em proved}' b'secure, md5 is believed to be at least as good as any other that maps' b'to a 128-bit digest. inversion should take about b'operations, and collision should take about operations. no' b'one has found a faster approach to inversion or collision.' b'' b'recent work by den boer and bosselaers \\cite{den-boer-md5} presents' b"a special kind of ``pseudocollision'' in md5's" b'internal compression function, which maps' b'a 512-bit message block $x$ and a' b'128-bit input state $s$ to a 128-bit output' b'state. they show how to find a message block $x$' b'and two related input states $s_1$ and $s_2$ that yield the same' b'output state: $f(x,s_1)$ $f(x,s_2)$. their well-thought approach' b'exploits structural properties of the collision function to find' b'a pseudocollision in about operations, much less than one' b'would expect.' b'' b'practical implications of this pseudocollision work to the security of' b'md5 are not evident. while a real collision in md5 implies a' b"pseudocollision (or a ``pseudo-inversion''), a" b'pseudocollision need not imply a real collision. indeed, a real' b'collision, since it involves two different messages, would almost' b'always involve {\\em different} message blocks $x_1$ and $x_2$ such that' b'$f(x_1,s_1) f(x_2,s_2)$, but the pseudocollisions have the same' b'message blocks. moreover, the input states $s_1$ and $s_2$ would' b"generally be unrelated, but the pseudocollisions' input states are" b'the same except for four bits. there does not seem to be any way to' b"extend den boer and bosselaers' approach to anything beyond the" b'special pseudocollisions, a limitation they readily admit.' b'' b'it is reasonable, therefore, to believe that md5 remains secure. while den' b'boer and bosselaers have found interesting structural properties in' b'md5, the properties seem only to lead to special pseudocollisions' b'and not anything approaching real collisions. further research, of' b'course, will give a better understanding of the strengths of md5 and' b'other message-digest algorithms, with the eventual hope that' b'such algorithms can, in some sense, be proved secure.' b'' b'\\bibliographystyle{plain}' b'\\begin{thebibliography}{1}' b'' b'\\bibitem{den-boer-md5}' b'bert den~boer and antoon bosselaers.' b'\\newblock collisions for the compression function of {md5}.' b"\\newblock in {\\it advances in cryptology eurocrypt b'\\newblock preprint.' b'' b'\\bibitem{rfc-md5}' b'r.l. rivest.' b'\\newblock {\\it {rfc} the {md5 message-digest algorithm}}.' b'\\newblock internet activities board, april b'' b'\\end{thebibliography}' b'' b'\\end{document}' 